academic-writing-and-citation-formats-in-turkey/#webpage"}}]}]}', "content_html" = '<div id="model-response-message-contentr_a67b1abffb24467d" class="markdown markdown-main-panel stronger enable-updated-hr-color" dir="ltr">
<p>In academic work in Turkey, internationally recognized citation formats are generally used. The most common are the <b>APA</b>, <b>MLA</b>, and <b>Chicago</b> styles. Which format you should use typically depends on your field of study or your professor&#8217;s preferences.</p>
<h3>The Most Commonly Used Formats</h3>
<h4>1. APA (American Psychological Association)</h4>
<ul>
<li>
<p><b>Used In:</b> It is widely used in the social sciences (psychology, education, sociology, etc.) and some natural sciences.</p>
</li>
<li>
<p><b>Features:</b> It is based on the author-date system. For in-text citations, the author&#8217;s last name and the publication year are used (e.g., (Yılmaz, 2020)). The reference list is arranged alphabetically.</p>
</li>
</ul>
<h4>2. MLA (Modern Language Association)</h4>
<ul>
<li>
<p><b>Used In:</b> It is preferred in the humanities (literature, linguistics, art, etc.).</p>
</li>
<li>
<p><b>Features:</b> It uses the author-page number system. In-text citations include only the author&#8217;s last name and the page number (e.g., (Yılmaz 45)). The reference list is provided alphabetically under the heading &#8220;Works Cited&#8221;.</p>
</li>
</ul>
<h4>3. Chicago</h4>
<ul>
<li>
<p><b>Used In:</b> It is used in history, art history, and some social sciences.</p>
</li>
<li>
<p><b>Features:</b> It has two different systems:</p>
<ul>
<li>
<p><b>Notes and Bibliography System:</b> Generally preferred in fields like history. A footnote is added at the bottom of the page for each source.</p>
</li>
<li>
<p><b>Author-Date System:</b> In-text citations are made in a similar way to the APA format.</p>
</li>
</ul>
</li>
</ul>
<h3>Key Points for Academic Writing</h3>
<ul>
<li>
<p><b>Consistency:</b> You must apply the rules of your chosen format consistently from beginning to end.</p>
</li>
<li>
<p><b>Originality:</b> You must always cite information taken from another source correctly. Failing to cite is considered <b>plagiarism</b>, a breach of academic ethics.</p>
</li>
<li>
<p><b>Accuracy:</b> You must ensure that all information in your reference list (author&#8217;s name, publication year, title, publisher, etc.) is correct and complete.</p>
</li>
</ul>
<p>Most universities or institutes specify their preferred format in their own thesis writing guidelines. Therefore, it is best to check your <b>school&#8217;s or department&#8217;s writing guide</b> before starting your work.</p>
<p>If you have any other questions about academic writing and citations, feel free to ask.</p>
</div>
<h2 class="wp-block-heading">University Practices</h2>
<ul class="wp-block-list">
<li><strong>YÖK Thesis Writing Guide</strong>: This sets the general framework for theses in Turkey.</li>
<li>Universities have their own <strong>institute writing guides</strong> (e.g., Hacettepe University, Istanbul University, METU).</li>
<li>Some institutes require APA, while others prefer ISNAD or Chicago.</li>
</ul>
<h2 class="wp-block-heading">What font is used in academic papers?</h2>
<p>The <strong>font</strong> used in academic papers in Turkey generally depends on the university&#8217;s or journal&#8217;s writing guide. However, the most widely accepted standards are as follows:</p>
<h3 class="wp-block-heading">Most Commonly Used Fonts</h3>
<ol class="wp-block-list">
<li><strong>Times New Roman</strong>
<ul class="wp-block-list">
<li>It is the most classic and most preferred font.</li>
<li>12-point font with 1.5 line spacing is considered standard.</li>
<li>The default font in many national and international journals.</li>
</ul>
</li>
<li><strong>Arial</strong>
<ul class="wp-block-list">
<li>Used by journals that want a simpler, more modern look.</li>
<li>11-point font is generally preferred.</li>
</ul>
</li>
<li><strong>Calibri</strong>
<ul class="wp-block-list">
<li>It has been preferred by some journals and universities, especially in recent years.</li>
<li>It is one of the default fonts in Microsoft Office.</li>
</ul>
</li>
</ol>
<h3 class="wp-block-heading">Special Cases</h3>
<ul class="wp-block-list">
<li><strong>Footnotes and bibliography</strong>: Generally written in 10–11 point font.</li>
<li><strong>Headings</strong>: Are made bold, and the size can be 12–14 point.</li>
<li><strong>Tables and figure captions</strong>: A smaller font size (10–11) can be used.</li>
<li><strong>Mathematical expressions and symbols</strong>: Can be written with fonts like <em>Cambria Math</em> or similar.</li>
</ul>
<h2 class="wp-block-heading">What is APA 7.0 format?</h2>
<p>APA 7.0, which stands for the <strong>Publication Manual of the American Psychological Association, 7th Edition</strong>, is the most common citation and referencing system used in academic writing, especially in the <strong>social sciences</strong>. It was published in 2019 and includes some changes from the previous version (APA 6.0).</p>
<h3 class="wp-block-heading">Key Features of APA 7.0</h3>
<ol class="wp-block-list">
<li><strong>Formatting</strong>
<ul class="wp-block-list">
<li>Font: <em>Times New Roman (12-point)</em>, <em>Calibri (11-point)</em>, <em>Arial (11-point)</em>, or <em>Georgia (11-point)</em> are acceptable.</li>
<li>Line spacing: Double-spaced.</li>
<li>Paragraph indent: 1.25 cm.</li>
<li>Page numbers: Top right corner.</li>
</ul>
</li>
<li><strong>In-Text Citations</strong>
<ul class="wp-block-list">
<li>The Author-Date system is used.</li>
<li>One author: (Yılmaz, 2020)</li>
<li>Two authors: (Yılmaz &amp; Demir, 2020)</li>
<li>Three or more authors: (Yılmaz et al., 2020)</li>
</ul>
</li>
<li><strong>Reference List Layout (References)</strong>
<ul class="wp-block-list">
<li>The author&#8217;s last name and first initial are written.</li>
<li>All sources are listed in <strong>alphabetical order</strong>.</li>
<li>A &#8220;hanging indent&#8221; is used for each source.</li>
</ul>
</li>
</ol>
<h3 class="wp-block-heading">Examples</h3>
<h4 class="wp-block-heading">Book</h4>
<p>Yılmaz, A. (2020). <em>Eğitimde teknoloji kullanımı</em> [The use of technology in education]. Ankara: Pegem Akademi.</p>
<h4 class="wp-block-heading">Book Chapter</h4>
<p>Demir, B. (2019). Eğitimde dijital dönüşüm [Digital transformation in education]. In A. Yılmaz (Ed.), <em>21. yüzyılda eğitim</em> [Education in the 21st century] (pp. 45–67). İstanbul: Beta.</p>
<h4 class="wp-block-heading">Article</h4>
<p>Kara, F., &amp; Yıldız, G. (2021). Öğrenme stillerinin akademik başarıya etkisi [The effect of learning styles on academic success]. <em>Eğitim Bilimleri Dergisi</em> [Journal of Educational Sciences], <em>15</em>(2), 123–135. <a>https://doi.org/10.1234/ebd.2021.5678</a></p>
<h4 class="wp-block-heading">Internet Source</h4>
<p>World Health Organization. (2020, March 27). <em>Mental health and COVID-19</em>. <a href="https://www.who.int/news-room" target="_blank" rel="noopener">https://www.who.int/news-room</a></p>
<h2 class="wp-block-heading">Some Differences Between APA 6.0 and 7.0</h2>
<ul class="wp-block-list">
<li>For sources with <strong>three or more authors</strong>, &#8220;et al.&#8221; is now used from the first citation (previously, this applied only to sources with four or more authors).</li>
<li>For internet sources, the <strong>retrieval date</strong> is only included if the content is likely to change over time.</li>
<li>DOI numbers are now presented in the format <strong><a>https://doi.org/</a></strong>.</li>
<li>The &#8220;Running head&#8221; requirement has been removed.</li>
